## Notes

From the book [Co-Intelligence: Living and Working with AI](https://www.amazon.com/Audible-Co-Intelligence-Living-Working-AI/dp/B0CNFCRJ77/ref=sr_1_1?crid=1A0LPYS8KZPXE&dib=eyJ2IjoiMSJ9.9KPiRiHYr0XqS5fH4QMLefQMWaVnxQ6LSQWYAk9cJVQfVomuUxmohojwRVAhfGO3UZhaSn0Nxk_74DhbAX_nka9pMHSSGVkPItwzYb9mck9b8E0W3G7o2kB2_MlNAYY5Z3rgyZI8ZOlDM8r_LKiiOlkgPE3gFuAVpBHqa9WwmIUXkrBWOnzi-x_Vx-sYlWs6Xogu8VJ0Q0h71WB-MeKgRojjso2nDJyQRqLKhGuzMvc.eCtu6K0X-pBRzHdvT3NiTi1d-CmL9VrJ6YHIYclVImE&dib_tag=se&keywords=Co-Intelligence%3A+living+and+Working+with+AI&qid=1773138278&sprefix=co-intelligence+living+and+working+with+ai%2Caps%2C256&sr=8-1),
we need to start in account the following principles when working with GenAI systems:

1. Always invite AI to the table.
2. You must be the human in the loop.
3. Treat AI as person, but tell it what kind of person it is.
4. Assume that this is the worst AI you will ever use.
